      "id":"tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/dec/19/the-returned-best-tv-2013",
      "sectionId":"tv-and-radio",
      "sectionName":"Television &amp; radio",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-12-19T07:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"The best TV of 2013: No 1 – The Returned (Channel 4)",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/dec/19/the-returned-best-tv-2013",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/dec/19/the-returned-best-tv-2013",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>John Crace:</strong> This French drama brilliantly subverted the conventional zombie tropes to create a TV programme unlike any other</p>",
        "headline":"The best TV of 2013: No 1 – The Returned (Channel 4)",
        "body":"<p>A French alpine town that exists both in concrete and in the imagination. A&nbsp;town connected to the rest of the world, yet wholly isolated. A&nbsp;town both in and out of time. A&nbsp;town where all the roads out seem inevitably to lead back; cars and buses drive for hours on a perpetual loop. The only person who seems to find this particularly surprising – or indeed, troubling – is the viewer.</p><p>The subtitled French drama The Returned was quite the classiest programme of the year. While unashamedly acknowledging its thriller and horror roots – Twin Peaks and The Omen to name just two – it brilliantly subverted the conventional zombie tropes to create a TV programme quite unlike anything that had been previously made.</p><p>At its heart was the existential question that is as profound as it is infrequently asked. What if the worst you could imagine wasn't having a child die in a car crash or having your fiance kill himself on your wedding day, but them coming back to life? Almost as they were before, but not quite.</p><p>The series opened with the reappearance of Camille, who had been killed in a coach crash four years earlier. She returned not as the conventional hollow-eyed zombie hell-bent on revenge on the living but as a recognisable, sentient being, albeit one who had been frozen in time and now looked four years younger than Lena, her twin sister. A teenaged girl who wanted to be loved and was just as troubled about what was happening to her as her sister and parents. Was she a gift from God, a punishment from the devil or was this just a different natural order?</p><p>Victor was the creepy boy who had watched his mother being murdered many years previously before being killed himself. He had many of the supernatural hallmarks of Damien in The Omen, but with an added childish innocence. His psychopathic tendencies were offset by the vulnerability of a young boy who just wants to be loved and looked after. One of Victor's murderers, Pierre, had now installed himself as a charismatic preacher in the town. Was he good or bad? It was never clear if even he himself knew.</p><p>Most drama series start off complicated and slowly offer up their secrets. The Returned started complex and became ever more so: as one storyline hinted at a resolution, another came along to further muddy the waters. The rules of engagement could only be hazily guessed at. While the dead could be killed and rekilled – Simon, Adele's ex-fiance, repeatedly self-resurrected – the possibility also began to emerge that it might not just be the dead who were dead. Perhaps the living were a different strain of the dead?</p><p>Then there was the psychopathic and dead Serge who had a predilection for killing and eating young women in the town's only underpass – a place best avoided – and his brother Toni. The dam that unaccountably started leaking to reveal a village that had been flooded decades before. The dead sheep and the hordes of the dead, or undead, that gathered in the woods.</p><p>Nothing much made sense, yet The Returned's atmospheric grip – not to mention fine performances from the central characters and a compelling soundtrack from Mogwai – was powerful enough to carry the audience through. It wasn't perfect, but then what is? As the series reached its end, a slight sense of cynicism did creep in. Were the producers deliberately blurring the script and fudging the revelations to set up the commercially important second series?</p><p>If they had held their nerve, resisted the siren call of cash and answered some of the questions – such as why Simon did kill himself on his wedding day – that really did need a first-series resolution, The Returned could have become an instant TV&nbsp;classic. As it is, it will just have to settle for being streets ahead of almost all its competition. Plus, there is always the upside that we will get another series to ease the longueurs of the 2014 summer schedules. But it's going to have to work hard to match the first.</p><p><em>• See the full countdown of the Best of TV of 2013 at </em><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio\" title=\"\"><em>theguardian.com/tv</em></a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/425322340|2013-12-19T13:23:07Z|0dc460e3e1c5de51b4c26f51874bf02ab78d9e37 -->",
