        "trailText":"Heather Mills is likely to be subject to disciplinary action after the International Paralympic Committee alleged she 'verbally abused' and 'physically harassed' an official",
        "headline":"Heather Mills alleged to have 'verbally abused' Paralympic official",
        "body":"<p>Heather Mills could be subject to disciplinary action after the International Paralympic Committee alleged she \"verbally abused\" and \"physically harassed\" an official.</p><p>Mills, the former wife of the Beatle Sir Paul McCartney, had said on Monday that she was abandoning <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/shortcuts/2013/aug/23/heather-mills-skiing-bring-paralympic-glory\" title=\"\">her hopes of skiing at the 2014 Sochi Paralympics</a> after the IPC ruled a new prosthetic leg she was competing on had not been ratified.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/25441200\" title=\"\">According to the BBC</a>, the IPC said that on hearing the news Mills went into a \"wild tantrum\". The IPC skiing committee head, Sylvana Mestre, claimed: \"I was trying to explain to [Mills] that this is not the equipment we approved earlier in the year and then that was it, she exploded. She jumped on me. She grabbed me from the back and she started to say that 'you don't know who I am, I will make your life miserable'.\"</p><p>In defence of Mills, 45, her coach John Clark said he planned to make a formal complaint about the behaviour of Mestre, claiming there was a \"vendetta\" against Mills and that Mestre had \"deliberately put barriers in the way\" to halt her progress.</p><p>A representative of the former model Mills said in a statement: \"Heather waited patiently to try and explain to Sylvana Mestre that her left boot was legal and purely cosmetic to abide by the archaic IPC rules. Sylvana shouted at Heather, would not let Tony [the GB coach] speak or explain, and stormed back to the boardroom raised table.\"</p><p>However, Craig Spence, head of media at the IPC, said: \"It was harassment. It was absolutely disgraceful behaviour.\" He added: \"It is likely we will sanction the athlete and this will incur a fine of between €500-€1,000.\"</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01np7vk\" title=\"\">Spence later told Radio 5</a> on Thursday morning that Mills had turned up uninvited for a coaches' meeting on Monday evening after having been told to stay away. He said their position was that she should submit fresh paper work on the prosthetic leg to the IPC and they would consider its eligibility.</p><p>\"Sylvana then went to explain this to Heather Mills and she never got as far as explaining it – Heather went into a rage that was witnessed by 10 coaches from other countries, who were shocked at what happened,\" he claimed. \"Heather verbally abused our official, she pushed her and had to be restrained by the two British coaches on site. We absolutely do not condone that.\"</p><p>Asked if there was any way back for Mills, Spence said: \"That's for her to decide. We have rules in place, we are likely to sanction her for her tantrum and if she submits an equipment form and her new prosthetics supplier takes liability for that in competition, then there's a chance we will sign that off, but the ball is very much in Heather Mills' court right now.\"</p><p>Mills lost the lower half of her left leg after a collision with a police motorbike in 1993. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/dec/16/heather-mills-2014-winter-paralympics-ski-team\" title=\"\">She was in the frame for the 2014 Winter Paralympics</a> after winning silver in the World Cup in New Zealand last August.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/425364628|2013-12-19T13:23:07Z|4e21d7a17815b642ba6d4ad9462fa18665286551 -->",
