      "id":"film/2013/dec/19/patrick-stewart-ian-mckellen-selfie",
      "sectionId":"stage",
      "sectionName":"Stage",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-12-19T09:58:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen – masters of the selfie",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/19/patrick-stewart-ian-mckellen-selfie",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/dec/19/patrick-stewart-ian-mckellen-selfie",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen have posted a picture of themselves sat on Santa's lap – and it's further proof of their mastery of the internet</p>",
        "headline":"Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen: masters of the selfie",
        "body":"<p>Patrick Stewart has unleashed the latest image to send the internet into fits of cooing: a <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/413352995297189888\">picture</a> of him and Ian McKellen sat on Santa's lap. Each are sporting Christmas jumpers – one red, one green – but are also wearing the bowler hats from their characters in Waiting For Godot that they're currently playing in New York, creating the most dissonant blend of high and low art since Twin Peaks. Words like \"adorable\" are being bandied about with a frequency usually reserved for baby showers.</p><p>It's all part of a merciless assault on the meme-osphere that McKellen and Stewart have calibrated with the power of their X-Men alter egos. They've been doing equally bromantic selfies in front of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/410902017138515968\">a Christmas tree</a>, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/406191641297698816\">carving a turkey on Thanksgiving</a>, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/400684079416635393\">hanging out by the Wall Steet bull</a> (with McKellen wearing a particularly swagged-out jacket), <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/390514596685307904\">getting boozed</a>, and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/400118216296759297\">bumping into</a> the God of funk and Twitter, Questlove.</p><p>This is just the most recent image dump – their recent trip to do <a href=\"http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/sir-patrick-stewart-narrowly-misses-bullseye-archery-photos-article-1.1432386\">some archery lessons</a> was equally adorable, and Stewart chalked the high water mark of selfies with his picture of himself <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SirPatStew/status/395960502083276801\">dressed as a lobster in a bathtub</a> for Halloween.</p><p>Why does this reduce the twitterati to jelly? The pair have built up an underground vault of goodwill and credibility from often very serious work – judiciously sprinkled with mainstream roles (Gandalf, Picard) that have cult fanboys gathering at their feet while their profiles also more generally rise. Now they're cashing in that sizable cultural capital, and their sudden immediacy and \"realness\" has everything clapping along in bewildered glee – so much so that their quite blatant viral marketing for their play is rendered entirely charming, even subliminal.</p><p>The pair also shamelessly play up to the version of \"Briddishness\" that Americans love: stentorian, even domineering, but also rather camp and twinkly. They explode everything Americans assume about us – that we're hopelessly repressed grumps – and everyone delights into the apparent unlikeliness of British people having fun and being silly (see also Monty Python). Where so often the British fetishise Hollywood success from one of our own, it's a reminder that Americans fetishise us: our supposed worldliness, class and heritage.</p><p>And while even the horniest schoolboy is getting jaded at yet another Kim Kardashian bum selfie (bumfie?), the thesp-love of these two is just so endearing that it'll probably never get old. We await the inevitable McKellen Easter Bunny costume with bated breath.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/425359529|2013-12-19T13:23:07Z|df1ebd891d8d92548145b4eb368a4004c4c0ac61 -->",
