        "trailText":"<p>Academy Award voters have reportedly been sent an anonymous printout of an article that states singer's song Young and Beautiful is not eligible for best original song prize</p>",
        "headline":"Is Lana Del Rey's Oscar campaign being sabotaged?",
        "body":"<p>Is someone trying to sabotage Lana Del Rey's Oscar campaign? Voters for this year's Academy Awards have apparently received a false news story alleging that Young And Beautiful should not be eligible for the best original song prize.</p><p>Young And Beautiful, from the soundtrack to The Great Gatsby, is one of 75 tracks longlisted for the Oscars' only song award. It was written for Baz Luhrmann's movie, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AnUHtjqEKjU\">appearing in trailers</a>, and is considered one of the frontrunners in a hotly contested <a href=\"http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/taylor-swift-beyonce-and-lana-del-rey-on-the-oscar-prowl-for-best-original-song\">prize category</a>.</p><p>But <a href=\"http://www.deadline.com/2013/12/great-gatsby-oscar-saboteur-targets-lana-del-rey-song-young-and-beautiful/\">according to Deadline</a> (<a href=\"http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5840339/lana-del-rey-best-song-oscar-bid-sabotaged\">via Billboard</a>), someone or something is trying to kill Young And Beautiful's chances. At least one member of the academy of motion picture arts and sciences' music selection committee has reportedly received \"an anonymous envelope\" with what looks like a print-out from the industry magazine Variety. The article, which was never actually published, claims that Lana Del Rey's song has been disqualified due to a release date technicality. Studio and label representatives were unable to trace the enevelope's sender.</p><p> Reading on mobile? <a href=\"http://www.muzu.tv/lana-del-rey/young-and-beautiful-music-video/1897118/\">Click here to watch</a></p><p>Smear campaigns are not unknown during Academy Awards season: as <a href=\"http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5840339/lana-del-rey-best-song-oscar-bid-sabotaged\">Billboard points out</a>, in 2004, a rumour circulated that Kathleen \"Bird\" York's song In The Deep was already several years old when it appeared on the soundtrack for Crash. That wasn't true.</p><p>The fake Variety story isn't Young And Beautiful's only problem. Hitfix's Kristopher Tapley <a href=\"http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/taylor-swift-beyonce-and-lana-del-rey-on-the-oscar-prowl-for-best-original-song#dHhaCQiuvoHFFjqG.99\">has described</a> a separate piece of gossip which recalls the operation against York. \"Somewhere along the line it was suggested that Lana Del Rey's [song] was partly conceived separate from [The Great Gatsby],\" he wrote in early November. \"If true, then ... it would [be] deemed ineligible ... Maybe it's not even true. I have no idea where that rumour originated.\"</p><p>Warner Bros, the studio that released The Great Gatsby, is apparently gearing-up its counter-offensive. They are currently putting the finishing touches on an online featurette which will highlight the song and its strong relationship to the film, as well as reminding jurors that Del Rey is absolutely eligible for her first Oscar.</p><p>Young And Beautiful is one of five Great Gatsby songs to be longlisted for the 86th Academy Awards. Coldplay, Arcade Fire and Will Ferrell's Ron Burgundy character are among the 75 nominees, which will be reduced to a final shortlist on 16 January.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/425363211|2013-12-19T13:23:07Z|791e2622801c332db6ad8471c7550b594ba92ea8 -->",
